Do R&D Expenses Have Any Impact on GDP?

Vitalii Rudko

December, 2020

Abstract

The first objective of this short empirical study is to establish whether there is any relationship between R&D expenses and GDP. The second objective is to conduct a correlation analysis of GDP components. In the first part, I used simple descriptive statistics methods in order to check whether there is any significant correlation between two. In the second part I used correlation analysis to check if there is a connection between the growth of R&D expenses and the components of GDP. In the last part, I conducted Granger causality test, that would help shed a light on usefulness of R&D variable in modelling GDP growth. I used FRED quarterly data for the period of 1990 - 2020.

1 Preparation

This section is technical, so it may be skipped.

#Loading data
##Reading csv files
rd <- read.csv2("D:/R_dir/GT/R&D.csv", sep = ",")
gdp <- read.csv2("D:/R_dir/GT/GDP.csv", sep = ",")
gce <- read.csv2("D:/R_dir/GT/GCE.csv", sep = ",")
gpdi <- read.csv2("D:/R_dir/GT/GPDI.csv", sep = ",")
netexp <- read.csv2("D:/R_dir/GT/NETEXP.csv", sep = ",")
pcec <- read.csv2("D:/R_dir/GT/PCEC.csv", sep = ",")

#Merging data
data <- gdp %>%
        right_join(rd) %>%
        right_join(gce) %>%
        right_join(gpdi) %>%
        right_join(netexp) %>% 
        right_join(pcec)

names(data) <- c("Date", "GDP", "RD", "GCE", "GDPI", "NETEXP", "PCEC")

##Formatting columns
data[,2:7] <- lapply(data[,2:7], as.numeric)

#Changing sign for NETEXP
data$NETEXP <- -1*data$NETEXP

##Creating dataframe with log returns.
data_log <- logret(data, omit_na = F)

##Changing sign for log returns of NETEXP
data_log$NETEXP <- -1*data_log$NETEXP
data$NETEXP <- -1*data$NETEXP

##Formatting Date column
data$Date <- as.Date(data$Date)
data_log$Date <- as.Date(data_log$Date)

##Subsetting data
data <- data %>% filter(Date >= "1990-01-01")
data_log <- data_log %>% filter(Date >= "1990-01-01")

#Creating time series
whole_ts <- xts(data_log[,3:7], order.by = data_log$Date)
core_ts <- xts(cbind(data_log$RD, data_log$GDPI, data_log$PCEC), order.by =  data_log$Date)
names(core_ts) <- c("RD", "GDPI", "PCEC")

2 GDP and R&D descriptive analysis

2.1 Actual series

Let’s start with plotting the actual series of GDP and R&D for the period of 1990-2020. We observe rising trends in both cases with two shocks in 2008 and 2020.

#Plotting real series. 
ggplot(data)+
  geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = GDP, col = "GDP"))+
  geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = RD, col = "R&D"))+
   scale_color_manual(name = "",
                     values = c("GDP" = "black",
                                "R&D"  = "red"))+
    labs(y = "Values ($ bln)", title = "US Quarterly GDP and R&D Actual Series")+
  theme_light()

Let’s take a closer look at the R&D series. Now It looks more like a GDP series, so there is definitely a correlation between two.

#Plotting real series R&D only. 
ggplot(data)+
  geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = RD), col = "red")+
    labs(y = "R&D ($ bln)",
         title = "US Quarterly R&D Actual Series")+
  theme_light()

Correlation test shows a strong statistically significant correlation between variables. Although correlation seems to be strong and significant there remains a good chance that it is spurious. Therefore we should take a first order log-difference in order to remove trends in our series.

#Testing correlation. 
cor.test(data$GDP, data$RD)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  data$GDP and data$RD
## t = 96.848, df = 121, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9908754 0.9955289
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9936115

2.2 Plotting log series

In this section we are going to remove trends and see what will happen. The plot of calculated growth rates is presented below, so we can notice a somewhat comovement of variables.

#Plotting lag 1 log differences. 
ggplot(data_log)+
  geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = GDP, col = "GDP"))+
  geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = RD, col = "R&D"))+
   scale_color_manual(name = "",
                     labels = c("GDP", "R&D"),
                     values = c("GDP" = "black",
                                "R&D"  = "red"))+
  labs(y = "Growth",
       title = "US Growth Rates of GDP and R&D")+
  theme_light()

This time correlation is not as high as previously, but still it is big enough and statically significant. However, that does not tell us much about the relationship between R&D and GDP. So, the further analysis is required.

#Testing correlation. 
cor.test(data_log$GDP, data_log$RD)

3 The GDP Component Descriptive Analysis

3.1 Plotting actual series

In this section I am going to decompose GDP into four basic components, namely: consumption, investments, government expenditures and net export. I used PCEC, GDPI, GSE and NETEXP data as a proxy for those variables. More details you can find in the appendix. It is better to plot every series separately in order to see trends. The plots are presented below. All series have growing trends, except NETEXP, which indicates actually the additional demand for capital. Apparently, the series are correlated, but it is not important to check those correlations, since they can be spurious, so I skip this part.

#Plotting real series. 
plot_1 <- ggplot(data)+
           geom_line(aes(x = Date, y = RD))+
    labs(y = "Values ($ bln)", title = "US Quarterly R&D Actual Series")+
  theme_light()

plot_2 <- ggplot(data)+

3.2 Plotting log series

As we can spot, the least volatile variable is government consumption and investments (GCE), and the most volatile one is the net export (NETEXP). Interestingly, we can observe a significant drop in growth rates of GDPI, PCEC, R&D and GCE, but not in NETEXP. The reason is obvious of course the overal consumption plummeted, thus the import rates as well, therefore NETEXP raised. It is hard to say if there is a significant correlation between any of the variables. The plots however give us a hint that we should check the series for stationarity condition later on before building any model. From now on I will work only with log series.

3.3 Current Correlation Analysis

Below is presented a lower triangle of the cross correlation matrix of the variables. The statistically insignificant values are crossed. We can drop GCE and NETEXP variables, since R&D is not correlated with them. The correlations themselves are discussed in details in the ‘Conclusions’ section.

#Calculating correlation matrix
core_corr <-cor(whole_ts)
core_corr_p <- cor_pmat(whole_ts)

##Plotting correlation matrix
ggcorrplot(core_corr, 
           hc.order = TRUE,
           lab = T,
           type = "lower",
           p.mat = core_corr_p)

3.4 Lagged cross correlation analysis

It is useful to look at the lagged CCF of a variable, just to see whether there is a correlation in a lagged term. As we see, there are significant feedback relations between R&D and GDP. There is also a unidirectional relationship between R&D and PCEC. PCEC and GDPI although seem to have no linear relationship.

#Plotting CCFs
plot1 <- ggCcf(data_log$RD, data_log$GDPI) +
         labs(title = "Series: R&D and GDPI")+
         theme_light()
plot2 <- ggCcf(data_log$RD, data_log$PCEC)+
         labs(title = "Series: R&D and PCEC")+
         theme_light()
plot3 <- ggCcf(data_log$PCEC, data_log$GDPI)+
         labs(title = "Series: PCEC and GDPI")+
         theme_light()

grid.arrange(plot1,
             plot2,
             plot3,
             ncol = 1)

4 VAR Model

4.1 VAR building

In this section I am going to use the VAR model in order to conduct the Granger causality test of variables. I decided to use an automatic selection, which suggested using the 1st or 3d order VAR model. After I restrict the model to statistically significant parameters. The report is presented below. The dependent variables are explained mostly by the autoregressive processes, only GDPI is dependent on PCEC.

#Building a model
model <- restrict(vars::VAR(core_ts, p = 3, type = "const"))

4.2 Residuals

It is important to check autocorrelation in residuals, they must be uncorrelated, and if fact they are not. The test accepted H0. Thus the model captures all of the relations.

#Testing serial correlation of residuals
model.serial <- serial.test(model, type = "PT.asymptotic")
model.serial
## 
##  Portmanteau Test (asymptotic)
## 
## data:  Residuals of VAR object model
## Chi-squared = 131.93, df = 117, p-value = 0.1634

The plots do not show correlations, which is good, but unfortunately one of the model’s assumptions is violated. The residuals are not normally distributed, so the model is nevertheless biased.

#Residuals graphical analysis R&D
plot(model.serial, names = "RD")

#Residuals graphical analysis R&D
plot(model.serial, names = "GDPI")

#Residuals graphical analysis R&D
plot(model.serial, names = "PCEC")

Normality test confirms violation of the normality assumption.

#Normality test
model.norm.test <- normality.test(model, multivariate.only = TRUE)
model.norm.test

CUSUM tests indeed show that the residuals follow random walk in almost all cases. However, PCEC submodel can be potentially misspecified, but the fluctuation is rather not significant.

#CUSUM test, graphical analysis.
model.cusum <- stability(model, type = "OLS-CUSUM")
plot(model.cusum)

4.3 Granger causality test

Finally we can conduct a Granger causality test, which, in short, shows no predictive value of the R&D variable in terms of GDPI and PCEC models, and vice versa.

#Granger causality test for R&D
model.cause1 <- causality(model, cause = "RD")
model.cause1
## $Granger
## 
##  Granger causality H0: RD do not Granger-cause GDPI PCEC
## 
## data:  VAR object model
## F-Test = 1.3591, df1 = 6, df2 = 330, p-value = 0.2306
## 
## 
## $Instant
## 
##  H0: No instantaneous causality between: RD and GDPI PCEC
## 
## data:  VAR object model
## Chi-squared = 21.795, df = 2, p-value = 1.85e-05
#Granger causality test for GDPI and PCEC
model.cause2 <- causality(model, cause = c("GDPI", "PCEC"))
model.cause2
## $Granger
## 
##  Granger causality H0: GDPI PCEC do not Granger-cause RD
## 
## data:  VAR object model
## F-Test = 0.94306, df1 = 6, df2 = 330, p-value = 0.4642
## 
## 
## $Instant
## 
##  H0: No instantaneous causality between: GDPI PCEC and RD
## 
## data:  VAR object model
## Chi-squared = 21.795, df = 2, p-value = 1.85e-05

5 Conclusions

There is a weak evidence for applying R&D variables in GDP growth modelling. There are statistically significant current correlations between GDP and the two main components of it. However, the high current correlations may only indicate the dependence of firms’ ability to finance R&D expenses on general economic situation, specifically on private consumption and on private investment, which is straightforward. Finally, the lagged values Of R&D variable fail to explain the growth of the components, therefore other variables should be considered for modelling GDP growth.

The correlation analysis revealed some interesting facts. Specifically, the government expenditures are not significantly correlated with anything. Therefore the macroeconomic situation does not influence GCE, at least in the short term, so it is independent. Another interesting finding is that, there is a higher negative correlation between GDPI and NETEXP, than between PCEC and NETEXP. It has a negative influence on GDP growth in the short term, since when domestic investment is high, the NETEXP is low, therefore the import is high as well. Also, that shows that the US economy depends on its own foreign investments. Other relations are rather obvious.
